STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS OF INTERMOUNTAIN GAS COMPANY
FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION Effective October 1, 2024
Contact Information
Lori A. Blattner Director of Regulatory Affairs Intermountain Gas Company PO Box 7608 208-377-6015 lori.blattner@intgas.com

INTERMOUNTAIN GAS COMPANY STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS Section 1 Introduction to Statement of Operating Conditions Intermountain Gas Company ("Transporter" or the "Company") has received a limited jurisdiction certificate of public convenience and necessity from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC"), pursuant to 18 C.F.R § 284.224, authorizing Company to transport gas through its own facilities to interconnections with an interstate pipeline for further transportation and consumption of such gas outside the State of Idaho. Transporter is utilizing, for transportation services provided hereunder, rates approved by the Idaho Public Utilities Commission ("Idaho PUC") for comparable in-state transportation service. The services to be provided under this Statement of Operating Conditions ("SOC") will use the Company's distribution facilities for the transportation of gas to an interconnection with Northwest Pipeline LLC ("Northwest"), an interstate pipeline company. The services shall be provided consistent with this SOC, including a signed Transportation Service Agreement in section 20. In the case of any difference between the SOC and a signed Transportation Service Agreement, the SOC shall rule. Section 2 Definitions 2.1. Access Fee The fee assessed by Intermountain for managing the RNG transportation facilities that provide gas producers access to the Intermountain distribution system. 2.2. Biogas Gas resulting from the anaerobic digestion of various sources of organic matter, including livestock operations, landfill and wastewater treatment facilities. 2.3. Biomethane Methane purified from biogas 2.4. Citygate A point at which Intermountain receives (or delivers) gas from Northwest Pipeline. 2.5. Constituent A chemical, compound, or material contained in a gas volume. 2.6. Custody Transfer Point or CTP The flange connection located at the outpost of the Producer facility and the inlet of the Interconnection Facilities. 2.7. Customer A person or entity (or agent thereof) that produces gas to be transported under this Statement of Operating Conditions and Transportation Service Agreement. 2.8. Delivery Point The Delivery Point may refer to one of two locations: 1) For volumes nominated by the Customer from the interstate pipeline system for its use at its production facility as a Customer taking service under the Companys Gas Tariff transportation rate schedules, the Delivery Point is the meter between Companys system and the Customers facilities. This point will normally be at the inlet of the Customers facility. 2) For gas volumes injected into the Companys distribution system to be delivered to Northwest Pipeline, the Delivery Point is the intertie or meter between the Companys distribution system and Northwest Pipeline located at the Export Facility. 2.9. Export Facilities Facilities required to compress and inject gas into Northwest Pipeline. 2.10. Export Facilities Maintenance Fee Used interchangeable with EFMF. The fee assessed for costs incurred by Intermountain to operate and maintain Export Facilities. 2.11. Gas Day A period of twenty-four consecutive hours, consistent with such Gas Day as defined in Northwest Pipeline's currently effective tariff. 2.12. Hazardous Waste Landfill All contiguous land and structures, and other appurtenances and improvements, on the land used for treatment, transfer, storage, resource recovery, disposal, or recycling of hazardous waste. The facility may consist of one or more treatment, transfer, storage, resource recovery, disposal, or recycling hazardous waste management units, or combinations of these units. This includes facilities permitted by the Department of Toxic Substance Control. 2.13. Idaho PUC The Idaho Public Utilities Commission, used interchangeable with I.P.U.C. The regulatory authority governing intrastate utility operations. 2.14. Interconnect Facilities Intermountain owned and controlled equipment that must be installed as part of the project between the CTP and Intermountains Pipeline Facilities. 2.15. Intermountain Intermountain Gas Company or Company. 2.16. Intermountain System Intermountain owned and operated local natural gas distribution facilities that provide natural gas transportation and sales services to retail customers. 2.17. Interruption A cessation of transportation or retail natural gas service deemed necessary by the Transporter. 2.18. Nomination The daily volume, in Dk, of gas requested by Customer for transportation and delivery to Customer at the Delivery Point over a 24-hour period commencing at 9:00 a.m. Mountain Time each day. 2.19. Maintenance Fee The fee assessed to recover costs incurred by Intermountain to operate and maintain RNG transportation facilities. 2.20. Maximum Daily Quantity ("MDQ") Customer's MDQ shall be specified in the Transportation Service Agreement in therms per day. All natural gas requirements over the contracted MDQ shall be delivered to Customer's Delivery Point(s) on an as available basis, at the reasonable discretion of the Company. Customer may request a change to its contracted MDQ on the anniversary date of any contract year during the term but any requested increase will be subject to availability at Company's reasonable discretion pursuant to its tariff and applicable rules. 2.21. Maximum Hourly Quantity ("MHQ") Customer's MHQ is specified in the Transportation Service Agreement in therms per hour. Hourly natural gas usage over the MHQ is interruptible and Customer will immediately reduce any excess usage over the MHQ upon Company's request. 2.22. Northwest Pipeline Used interchangeable with Northwest. The Northwest Pipeline LLC, operated by Williams Corporation. Northwest Pipeline is used as the interstate pipeline to transport natural gas. 2.23. Pipeline Facilities All Intermountain owned and controlled pipelines and equipment that must be installed between the Interconnect Facilities and Intermountain's System to enable the transportation of Producer's RNG from the Interconnect Facilities to Intermountain's System. 2.24. Pooling Pools, or Pooling, are nominations that allow customers (typically agents) to aggregate multiple customers volumes into one single Receipt Point. 2.25. Producer Provider and/or Supplier of RNG proposing to inject biogas / RNG into Intermountains pipeline. 2.26. Purchase Gas Adjustment Used interchangeable with PGA. An annual adjustment mechanism assessed to retail natural gas customers to recover the weighted average cost of gas. 2.27. Rate Schedule T-3 Intermountain's rate schedule within its Gas Tariff approved and governed by the Idaho PUC. 2.28. Receipt Point The Receipt Point may refer to one of two locations: 1) For volumes nominated by the Customer from the interstate pipeline system for its use at its production facility as a gas customer taking service under the Companys Gas Tariff transportation rate schedules, the Receipt Point is the Citygate or Pools where Customers volumes are scheduled. 2) For RNG volumes injected into Intermountains distribution system to be delivered to Northwest Pipeline, the Receipt Point is the intertie or meter between Intermountains distribution system and Customers facilities. 2.29. Renewable Natural Gas Gas produced from agricultural, municipal waste or biogas that, with or without further processing, has characteristics that (a) are consistent with the Gas Quality Specifications set forth in Section 5 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, (b) does not pose a hazard to inclusion in the Company's transportation and/or distribution lines and (c) does not otherwise pose a hazard when comingled with natural gas. 2.30. Shipper Used interchangeably with Customer. 2.31. Transportation Service Agreement The agreement containing the terms and conditions whereby Intermountain agrees to provide applicable transportation service to Customers on its distribution system. 2.32. Transporter Used interchangeably with Intermountain Gas Company or the Company in this Statement of Operating Conditions and Transportation Service Agreement. Section 3 Statement of Currently Effective Rates 3.1. INTERRUPTIBLE TRANSPORTATION SERVICE · Availability: Available at any mutually agreeable delivery point on the Company's distribution system to any Customer upon execution of a one-year minimum written Transportation Service Agreement for interruptible transportation service. A pro forma Transportation Service Agreement is included in Section 20 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. · Rate Schedule T-3: Customer Charge: $300.00 per month Per Therm Charge: Block One: First 100,000 therms transported @ $0.03489 Block Two: Next 50,000 therms transported @ $0.01299 Block Three: Over 150,000 therms transported @ $0.00349 · Annual Minimum Bill: The customer shall be subject to the payment of an annual minimum bill based on annual usage of 200,000 therms. The deficit usage below 200,000 therms shall be billed at the T-3 Block 1 rate. An annual minimum bill will not apply if the customer is a renewable natural gas production facility. 3.2. EXPORT FACILITY MAINTENANCE SERVICE: · Availability: Available to any Interruptible Transportation Service Customer that has a Delivery Point at the meter between the Company's distribution system and Northwest Pipeline. · Rate: $5,400 per month · The Monthly Export Facility Maintenance Fee ("EFMF") recovers costs incurred to operate and maintain compression facilitates needed to pump gas from Company's distribution system into Northwest Pipeline. The EFMF is paid only by Customers with a Transportation Service Agreement with a Delivery Point at the meter between the Company's distribution system and Northwest Pipeline. The EFMF is calculated by a formula, as described in the Intermountain RNG Facilitation Plan, and is updated annually effective October 1. Any changes made to the rate in this Statement of Currently Effective Rates will be included in a compliance filing submitted by Company no later than October 31 of each year. · Approved by the Idaho PUC in Order No. 35891, Case No. INT-G-23-03 (August 15, 2023). 3.3. MAINTENANCE SERVICE: · Availability Available to any producer needing to transport gas from an RNG facility to the Company's distribution system. · Rate: $3,445 per month · The Monthly Maintenance Fee recovers costs incurred by Company to transport gas from an RNG facility to the Company's distribution system. The Maintenance Fee is calculated by a formula, as described in the Intermountain RNG Facilitation Plan, and is updated annually effective October 1. Any changes made to the rate in this Statement of Currently Effective Rates will be included in a compliance filing submitted by Company no later than October 31 of each year. · Approved by the Idaho PUC in Order No. 34693, Case No. INT-G-20-03 (June 12, 2020) as further revised by Order No. 35891, Case No. INT-G-23-03 (August 15, 2023). 3.4. MONTHLY ACCESS FEE: · Rate: $8,000 per month · The Monthly Access Fee compensates Company for the management of the transportation facilities that connect RNG production plants to the distribution system. The Access Fee is calculated as described in the RNG Facilitation Plan, and is fixed until changed by the Idaho PUC. · Approved by the Idaho PUC in Order No. 35891 Case No. INT-G-23-03 (August 15, 2023).
Section 4 Availability and Characterization of Service The service to be provided under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be interruptible. Such service shall be available to any qualified applicant upon the execution of a Transportation Service Agreement between Company and Customer. A pro forma Transportation Service Agreement is included in Section 20 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. Company reserves the right to refuse the commencement of service, or to discontinue service, where, in the Company's reasonable discretion, (1) the service would impair its primary public service obligation pursuant to regulation by the Idaho PUC, or (2) the service would require or result in a change to Intermountain' s jurisdictional or regulatory status. Company has no standing obligations to provide service hereunder other than interruptible service which is at all times subordinate to any and all firm services provided by Intermountain as part of its natural gas distribution operations. Section 5 Gas Quality Specifications, Monitoring and Testing 5.1. RNG delivered to an Intermountain Receipt Point must meet quality specifications of this section. 5.2. RNG shall be commercially free from objectionable odors (excluding odorant), solid matter, dust, gums, and gum forming constituents, or any other substance which interferes with the intended purpose of merchantability of the gas or causes interference with the proper and safe operation of the lines, meters, regulators or other appliances through which it may flow. Inline filtering to achieve a max particle level of no more than three (3) microns is required. 5.3. RNG shall not contain any toxic or hazardous substance in concentrations which may be, in the normal use of the gas, hazardous to health, injurious to pipeline facilities, a limit to merchantability or contrary to applicable government standards. 5.4. RNG must be free from bacteria, pathogens and any other substances injurious to utility facilities or that would cause the RNG to be unmarketable. 5.5. RNG received by Intermountain may be supplied to end users as a discreet RNG supply or as a mixed gas supply blended with natural gas or different RNG provided by others. 5.6. Transporter shall have unqualified right to comingle RNG received for service hereunder with gas from other sources. Accordingly, RNG received by Transporter shall be subject to such changes as may result from such comingling and Transporter shall, notwithstanding any other provisions herein, be under no obligation to deliver for Shipper's account gas identical to that received by Transporter. 5.7. Gas from Hazardous Waste Landfills and associated systems cannot be injected into Intermountains pipeline. Producer must certify that the gas it delivers to Intermountain was not derived from a Hazardous Waste Landfill or associated systems. 5.8. If RNG tendered to Transporter fails to meet the specifications set forth in this Statement of Operating Conditions, the measuring party shall notify the other party of such failure. The receiving party may refuse to accept such RNG. The party tendering non-specification gas hereunder shall indemnify the receiving party for any injury, damage, loss or liability caused by the delivery of such gas. 5.9. 5.11. PERIODIC SAMPLING 5.11.1 Periodic sampling frequency will vary according to which of three phases of the project then applies. 5.11.1.1 Start Up & Break-In Phase lasting sixty (60) days after the first RNG is introduced into the pipeline system. 5.11.1.2. Initial Production Run Phase lasting seven hundred and thirty (730) days following the end of the Startup & Break-In Phase. 5.11.1.3. Mature Production Run Phase encompasses the balance of the operational life of Intermountains Receipt Facilities. 5.11.2. Sampling frequencies are approximate and may vary slightly based on production demands and availability. Table 3 shows the array of periodic sampling frequencies dependent upon the phase of RNG production: Table 3 Periodic Sampling Frequencies
Table 3 Periodic Sampling Frequencies
Start-Up & Break-In Phase (60 days) Initial Production Run Phase (730 days after startup) Mature Production Run Phase A Weekly Every 180 days Annual B One Sample Not Analyzed Every 5 years
5.11.3. Producer shall procure and furnish all materials, equipment, supplies, services and labor required for periodic sampling extraction and analysis. RNG samples shall be extracted for laboratory analysis at a sample point upstream of the Custody Transfer Point. The sample point shall be an inline probe and must be separate from the sample point used for continuous sampling. 5.11.4. Samples will be collected in Summa canisters for VOCs and permanent gases. Double samples will be drawn into Tedlar bags with non- metallic fittings for sulfur compounds, drawn as late in the day as permitted for overnight shipping in order to meet 24-hour hold times. Testing of samples in Tedlar bags received after 24-hour hold times may be accepted at the discretion of Intermountain. Samples will be sealed and transported using established and customary sampling procedures. Samples will be sent by the Producer to a third-party analytical laboratory approved by Intermountain and Producer for analysis. All test results will be shared with Intermountain within five (5) calendar days of the test results being received by Producer. Producer shall be responsible for all costs associated with such testing.
5.12. RNG received by Intermountain may be subject to interchangeability testing per American Gas Association (AGA) Research Bulletin 36 in order to satisfy requests of Intermountain or Intermountains customers. 5.13. Producer shall provide notice to Intermountain a minimum of 48 hours in advance of scheduled gas sample extractions to allow the Parties an opportunity to observe the procedure. No blending of the constituents shown in Table 2 will be allowed.
5.14. COSTS RELATED TO QUALITY MONITORING 5.14.1. Producer and Intermountain shall execute a facilities agreement that outlines the terms and conditions under which Producer will inject RNG into Intermountains distribution system. As part of the facilities agreement, Producer shall pay Intermountains costs for all engineering, procurement and construction of quality monitoring systems. Such expenses shall include, but not be limited to, sample fittings, piping, analyzers, equipment enclosures, related permits, land rights, odorizing equipment, communication equipment, software, programming costs, design costs and other expenses. Intermountain shall own and operate all related facilities as referenced in the facilities agreement. 5.14.2. Producer shall be responsible for the cost of analytical testing prior to the initial interconnection. 5.14.3. Unless otherwise agreed upon, Intermountain shall continuously monitor selected gas quality specifications to detect gas generation process conditions. Specifications monitored will commonly include those listed in the Tables 1 and 2.
5.15. RNG MONITORING REQUIREMENT PRIOR TO INITIAL INTERCONNECTION 5.15.1. Testing prior to interconnection to Intermountains facilities will be the responsibility of Producer using independent certified testing facilities. Results are to be shared with Intermountain within five (5) calendar days of the time results are received by the Producer. 5.15.2. RNG shall be analyzed at a minimum of two (2) different intervals over a two to four week period prior to interconnection to detect parameters or components listed in Table 1. Tests should occur with RNG production operating at a steady state and at the anticipated normal production capacity. The two tests must be performed at least five days apart. Testing should be conducted using analytical methods and techniques considered acceptable in the natural gas industry. RNG cannot be injected into Intermountains facilities if any parameter fails to comply with quality limits listed in Tables 1 and 2. 5.15.3. RNG can be injected into Intermountains facilities if the RNG meets all the requirements of these Gas Quality Specifications.
5.16. RNG MONITORING REQUIREMENT DURING OPERATION 5.16.1. Testing during active flow into Intermountains facilities at the interconnection will be the responsibility of Intermountain using continuous real-time monitoring. Results are to be shared with Producer in a timely manner. Testing of raw RNG and RNG upstream from the interconnection during this period will be the responsibility of Producer. 5.16.2. Intermountain shall provide continuous real-time or near-real time monitoring for selected natural gas properties of RNG listed in Table 1. Compliance shall be assessed using a 4 8 minute monitoring interval. Intermountain may refuse to accept any RNG or interrupt the flow of any RNG which does not meet specifications listed in this section of the Statement of Operating Conditions.
5.17. NEGATIVE RESULTS 5.17.1. If there are increases in the levels of certain detected constituents that 1) interferes with the intended purpose of merchantability of the gas, or 2) causes interference with the proper and safe operation of pipelines, meters, regulators or other appliances through which the gas may flow, Producer shall provide written notification to Intermountain of such increases. The sampling frequency for such constituents will be reset to the sampling frequency applicable to the previous phase until three (3) consecutive acceptable or non-negative" results are achieved with respect to such constituents. For instance, if a high result is noted during the Initial Production Run Phase, then that constituent class will be sampled in accordance with the sampling frequency associated with the Startup/ Break-In Phase.
5.18. CHANGES 5.18.1. Changes to Producers gas quality plan can be made by the Producer as warranted to fit changing production needs and/or conditions at upstream facilities, provided that Intermountain approves such changes in writing in advance of implementation.
5.19. SPECIAL TESTS 5.19.1. Intermountain may request special testing at any time with reasonable advance notice to Producer if Intermountain has a specific concern with the gas quality plan or sampling results. The cost of such testing will be borne by Producer.
5.20. RNG DELIVERY PROCESS CHANGES 5.20.1. Producer must notify Intermountain prior to changing the RNG production and delivery system. Prospective changes may include, but not be limited to, feedstock changes, Biogas conditioning equipment changes, Biogas process condition changes, system control changes, addition or deletion of process equipment or operating parameters and other modifications.
5.21. RESUMPTION OF RNG FLOW AFTER INTERRUPTION 5.21.1. After interruption by either Producer or Intermountain, RNG flow into Intermountains facilities may be restarted after Producer can successfully prove compliance with the properties listed in Tables 1 and 2. Compliance shall be demonstrated when two (2) continuous and consecutive monitoring intervals in real-time or near-real time has indicated that Producers RNG is within the limits presented in Tables 1 and 2.
5.22. WAIVER PROVISION 5.22.1. Intermountain, in its reasonable judgement, may elect, but is not obligated to, on a non-discriminatory basis to waive Producers obligation to conform with certain gas quality specifications, provided that such waiver does not interfere with Intermountains ability to fulfill its obligations to other parties. Any such waiver is temporary and is without prejudice to Intermountains right hereunder or any other rights which it may have, including without limitation, Intermountains right to reject other non-conforming gas.
5.23. GAS QUALITY REVISIONS 5.23.1 Intermountain may seek Commission approval of revisions to the gas quality specifications from time-to-time at Intermountains discretion as sampling and testing standards and methods evolve.
Section 6 Daily Nomination Requirements 6.1. Unless otherwise agreed to, on a daily basis, the Customer or Customer's agent shall provide to the Company no later than noon, Mountain Standard Time, the following information (a) The meter read, as of that day, for gas delivered to the Receipt Point during the immediately preceding twenty-four (24) hour period unless telemetered volumes have been previously agreed to by Company and the Customer, and (b) The therms to be nominated for delivery from Customer's production facility to Company's distribution system for the Gas Day beginning at 8:00 a.m., Mountain Time, must be communicated to Intermountain no later than 11:00 a.m., one (1) working day prior to the Gas Day except on the first working calendar day of the month shall be due two (2) working days prior to Gas Day. (c) The Customer or Customer's agent may request, and the Company shall use all reasonable efforts to accommodate, a renomination or a volume change after the original Gas Day nomination. (d) The Company has the right to refuse receipt of any volumes which exceed the Customer's applicable contracted quantity at the Receipt Point, and at no time shall the Company be required to deliver quantities of gas at a Delivery Point in excess of the quantities of gas tendered by Customer at Transporter's Receipt Point. Section 7 Imbalance and Penalty Provisions 7.1. Monthly The Customer or Customer's agent shall be responsible for balancing all volumes of customer-owned gas delivered to the Company's distribution system. At the end of month, Intermountain shall determine Customers distribution system imbalance by subtracting volumes injected into the interstate pipeline system via the Export Facilities from the sum of total deliveries of gas injected into Intermountains system for that month plus the prior months imbalance (Net Delivery). If the sum of that months billed usage for Customers agents transportation customers exceeds the Net Delivery amount, the imbalance is zero. If the sum of that months billed usage for Customers Agents transportation customers is less than the Net Delivery amount, the imbalance is equal to the Net Delivery less the sum of that months billed usage for Customers Agents transportation customers. If the imbalance is more than five percent (5%) of Customers total monthly injections into Companys distribution system, Company shall notify the Customer or Customer's agent that an imbalance penalty situation exists. Such notification shall be given no later than fifteen (15) days subsequent to the end of the month for which receipts or deliveries of gas were made. The Customer or Customer's agent shall have forty-five (45) non-entitlement days from the date of notification to balance its distribution system deliveries of gas within the five percent (5%) tolerance level. If at the end of such balancing period, the volume imbalance is not within the five percent (5%) tolerance level, a penalty shall be placed upon the Customer by the Company as follows: (a) The Customer shall pay the Company a penalty of $1.00 (one dollar) per therm, applied to the volume above the five percent (5%) level plus one of the following: (b) Company shall purchase the excess of gas over the five percent (5%) level. Company shall have the right to elect the purchase price of the imbalance gas at the lessor of (1) its approved Weighted Average Cost of Gas, or (2) the average 30-day spot price for gas delivered at the Canadian border and the Rocky Mountain region as reported by the Inside FERC Gas Market Report, first of month publication for the applicable delivery month. (c) With the approval of Company, which shall not be unreasonably withheld, Customer may agree to sell a portion of its imbalance to another Producer or Producers Agent that has volumes injected into Companys Export Facility. Customer must provide a written document, signed by both parties, showing the amount of imbalance transferred. The Producer selling an imbalance may only sell or transfer up to the total imbalance and the purchasing Producer shall not reduce its imbalance below zero percent (0%) or increase it above five percent (5%). In any event, Customer shall not be relieved of its obligation to also balance its direct or pooled nominations at the point between Northwest Pipeline and Companys distribution system pursuant to Companys approved Tariff. Section 8 Warranty Agent or Shipper warrants that it will have title to all gas it tenders or causes to be tendered to the Company, and such gas shall be free and clear of all liens and adverse claims and agent, or Shipper shall indemnify the Company against all damages, costs, and expenses of any nature whatsoever arising from every claim against said gas. Section 9 Payment 9.1. All billings rendered shall be net and each monthly bill shall be due and payable no less than 22 days from the date of rendition. When the customer account is participating in the electronic transfer of funds, the billings shall be due, payable, and transferred on the bill due date (no less than 22 days from the date of bill rendition). 9.2. The respective obligations of Company and Customer, whether in contract or not, are subject to valid laws, orders, and rules of the Idaho Public Utilities Commission and any other authority having jurisdiction thereof. 9.3. Past due bills are subject to a late payment charge of 1% per month or approximately 12% annually. Section 10 Creditworthiness The Company shall determine the creditworthiness of an applicant or Customer in an equitable and non-discriminatory manner. A Customer shall be deemed creditworthy if it has no delinquent bills to the Company for gas service within the last twenty-hour (24) months and, within the last two (2) years has not: (a) had service disconnected for nonpayment or (b) filed a voluntary petition, has a pending petition, or has an involuntary petition filed against it, under any bankruptcy or insolvency law. For purposes of this determination a contested bill shall not be considered delinquent. In determining the creditworthiness of applicants, the Company shall consider the size of the credit exposure and the availability of objective and verifiable information about the applicant. The Company may consider the applicant's payment history from other utilities and verifiable conditions such as, but not limited to: applicant's independently audited annual and quarterly financial statements, including an analysis of its leverage, liquidity, profitability, and cash flows; and credit rating agency information. The Company may require from an uncreditworthy Customer, as a guarantee against the non-payment of bills, a deposit payable in cash or by letter of credit in an amount equal to the amount owed to Company by Customer in the two (2) months with the highest bills based upon the most recent twelve (12) months period, or two (2) months of projected billing for an applicant. For Customers with multiple accounts, each account will be treated individually for purposes of this rule. If the Company requires a deposit as a condition of providing service, upon request of the Customer or applicant, the Company must: (a) provide written explanation of the facts upon which the Company based its decision; and (b) provide the applicant or Customer with an opportunity to rebut the facts and show other facts demonstrating its creditworthiness. In the case of a cash deposit as a guarantee against the payment of bills, interest thereon at the rate established by Section 154.501(d) of FERC's Regulations shall be paid by the Company for the times such deposit is held by the Company. Upon a Customer's annual request, Company will credit any accrued interest to the Customer's bill. Upon discontinuance of service, the amount of the final bill will be deducted from the sum of the deposit and interest due, and the balance, if any, shall be remitted to the depositor. Section 11 Metering and Measurement Company will meter the quantity of gas received from Customer at the Receipt Point and the quantity of gas delivered to Customer at the Delivery Point identified in the Transportation Service Agreement. 11.1. The Customer shall provide a suitable location satisfactory to the company for its metering equipment. 11.2. The representative of the Company shall be given access to the premises of the Customer at all reasonable hours for obtaining meter readings for inspection of piping and for inspecting, removing, repairing or protecting from abuse or fraud any of the property of Company installed on the premises. Access shall be granted at all times for emergency purposes. The Company may refuse gas service, or suspend it, on refusal of legitimate access to the property.
